# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azoospermia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] These agents inhibit the enzyme 5α-reductase, which is involved in the metabolic transformations of a variety of endogenous steroids.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] 5-ARIs are most known for preventing conversion of testosterone, the major androgen sex hormone, to the more potent androgen dihydrotestosterone (DHT), in certain androgen-associated disorders.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] 5-ARIs can be used in the treatment of hirsutism in women.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] The usefulness of 5-ARIs for the potential treatment of acne is uncertain.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] 5-ARIs are sometimes used as antiandrogens in feminizing hormone therapy for transgender women to help reduce body hair growth and scalp hair loss.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] They have also been explored in the treatment and prevention of prostate cancer.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] While the 5-ARI finasteride reduces the cancer risk by about a third, it also increases the fraction of aggressive forms of prostate cancer.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Overall, there does not seem to be a survival benefit for prostate cancer patients under finasteride.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Finasteride (brand names Proscar, Propecia) inhibits the function of two of the isoenzymes (types 2 and 3) of 5α-reductase.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] It decreases circulating DHT levels by up to about 70%.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Dutasteride (brand name Avodart) inhibits all three 5α-reductase isoenzymes and can decrease DHT levels by 95%.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] It can also reduce DHT levels in the prostate by 97 to 99% in men with prostate cancer.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Epristeride (brand names Aipuliete, Chuanliu) is marketed in China for the treatment of benign prostatic hyperplasia.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] However, it can only decrease circulating DHT levels by about 25 to 54%.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Alfatradiol (brand names Ell-Cranell Alpha, Pantostin) is a topical 5-ARI used to treat pattern hair loss in Europe.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] 5-ARIs are generally well tolerated in both men and women and produce few side effects.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] However, they have been found to have some risks in studies with men, including slightly increased risks of decreased libido, erectile dysfunction, ejaculatory dysfunction, infertility, breast tenderness, gynecomastia, depression, anxiety, self-harm, and dementia.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] In addition, although 5-ARIs decrease the overall risk of developing prostate cancer, they have been found to increase the risk of developing certain rare but high-grade forms of prostate cancer.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] As a result, the FDA has notified healthcare professionals that the Warnings and Precautions section of the labels for the 5-ARI class of drugs has been revised to include new safety information about the increased risk of being diagnosed with these rare but more serious forms of prostate cancer.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Finasteride has also been associated with intraoperative floppy iris syndrome and cataract formation.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Depressive symptoms and suicidality have been reported.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Sexual dysfunction, including erectile dysfunction, loss of libido, and reduced ejaculate, may occur in 3.4 to 15.8% of men treated with finasteride or dutasteride.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] This is linked to lower quality of life and can cause stress in relationships.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] There is also an association with lowered sexual desire.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] It has been reported that in a subset of men, these adverse sexual side effects may persist even after discontinuation of finasteride or dutasteride.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] 5-ARIs have a small risk of breast changes in men including breast tenderness and gynecomastia (breast development/enlargement).
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] There is no association of 5-ARIs with male breast cancer.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] After the initial 18 months of therapy, the risk of self-harm was no longer heightened, whereas the elevation in risk of depression lessened but remained marginally increased (HR, 1.22; 95% CI, 1.08–1.37).
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] The absolute increase in the rate of depression was 247 per 100,000 patient-years and of self-harm was 17 per 100,000 patient-years.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] As such, on the basis of these findings, it has been stated that cases of depression in patients that are attributable to 5-ARIs will be encountered on occasion, while cases of self-harm attributable to 5-ARIs will be encountered very rarely.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] There were no differences in the rates of depression, self-harm, and suicide between finasteride and dutasteride, suggesting that the specific 5-ARI used does not influence the risks.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] The absolute risks of self-harm and depression with 5-ARIs remain low (0.14% and 2.0%, respectively).
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] The pharmacology of 5α-reductase inhibition is complex, but involves the binding of NADPH to the enzyme followed by the substrate.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Specific substrates include testosterone, progesterone, androstenedione, epitestosterone, cortisol, aldosterone, and deoxycorticosterone.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] The entire physiologic effect of their reduction is unknown, but likely related to their excretion or is itself physiologic.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] 5α-Reductase reduces the steroid Δ4,5 double bond in testosterone to its more active form DHT.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Thus, inhibition results in decreased amounts of DHT.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Because of this, slight elevations in testosterone and estradiol levels occur.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] The 5α-reductase reaction is a rate-limiting step in the testosterone reduction and involves the binding of NADPH to the enzyme followed by the substrate.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Beyond being a catalyst in the rate-limiting step in testosterone reduction, 5α-reductase isoforms I and II reduce progesterone to 5α-dihydroprogesterone (5α-DHP) and deoxycorticosterone to dihydrodeoxycorticosterone (DHDOC).
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] In vitro and animal models suggest subsequent 3α-reduction of DHT, 5α-DHP and DHDOC lead to neurosteroid metabolites with effect on cerebral function.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] These neurosteroids, which include allopregnanolone, tetrahydrodeoxycorticosterone (THDOC), and 3α-androstanediol, act as potent positive allosteric modulators of GABAA receptors, and have antidepressant, anxiolytic, prosexual, and anticonvulsant effects.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] 5α-Dihydrocortisol is present in the aqueous humor of the eye, is synthesized in the lens, and might help make the aqueous humor itself.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] 5α-Dihydroaldosterone is a potent antinatriuretic agent, although different from aldosterone.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Its formation in the kidney is enhanced by restriction of dietary salt, suggesting it may help retain sodium.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] 5α-DHP is a major hormone in circulation of normal cycling and pregnant women.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Other enzymes compensate to a degree for the absent conversion of 5α-reductase, specifically with local expression at the skin of reductive 17β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase, and oxidative 3α-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase and 3β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase enzymes.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] In BPH, DHT acts as a potent cellular androgen and promotes prostate growth; therefore, DHT blockers inhibit and alleviate symptoms of BPH.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] In alopecia, male and female-pattern baldness is an effect of androgenic receptor activation, so reducing levels of DHT also reduces hair loss.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Finasteride was the first 5-ARI to be introduced for medical use.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] It was marketed for the treatment of BPH in 1992 and was subsequently approved for the treatment of pattern hair loss in 1997.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Epristeride was the second 5-ARI to be introduced and was marketed for the treatment of BPH in China in 2000.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] Dutasteride was approved for the treatment of BPH in 2001 and was subsequently approved for pattern hair loss in South Korea in 2009 and in Japan in 2015.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] The patent protection on finasteride and dutasteride has expired and both drugs are available as generic medications.
[src:azoospermia/5α-reductase-inhibitor] 5-ARIs have been studied in combination with the nonsteroidal antiandrogen bicalutamide for the treatment of prostate cancer.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Acute prostatitis may be a complication of prostate biopsy.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Often, the prostate gland is very tender to palpation through the rectum.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Acute prostatitis is relatively easy to diagnose due to its symptoms that suggest infection.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] The organism may be found in blood or urine, and sometimes in both.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Common bacteria are *Escherichia coli, Klebsiella, Proteus, Pseudomonas, Enterobacter, Enterococcus, Serratia,* and *Staphylococcus aureus.* This can be a medical emergency in some patients and hospitalization with intravenous antibiotics may be required.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] A complete blood count reveals increased white blood cells.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Sepsis from prostatitis is very rare, but may occur in immunocompromised patients; high fever and malaise generally prompt blood cultures, which are often positive in sepsis.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] A prostate massage should never be done in a patient with suspected acute prostatitis, since it may induce sepsis.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Since bacteria causing the prostatitis is easily recoverable from the urine, prostate massage is not required to make the diagnosis.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Rectal palpation usually reveals an enlarged, exquisitely tender, swollen prostate gland, which is firm, warm, and, occasionally, irregular to the touch.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] C-reactive protein is elevated in most cases.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Antibiotics are the first line of treatment in acute prostatitis.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Antibiotics usually resolve acute prostatitis infections in a very short time, however a minimum of two to four weeks of therapy is recommended to eradicate the offending organism completely.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Appropriate antibiotics should be used, based on the microbe causing the infection.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Some antibiotics have very poor penetration of the prostatic capsule, others, such as ciprofloxacin, trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole, and tetracyclines such as doxycycline penetrate prostatic tissue well.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] In acute prostatitis, penetration of the prostate is not as important as for category II because the intense inflammation disrupts the prostate-blood barrier.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] It is more important to choose a bactericidal antibiotic (kills bacteria, e.g., a fluoroquinolone antibiotic) rather than a bacteriostatic antibiotic (slows bacterial growth, e.g. tetracycline) for acute potentially life-threatening infections.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Severely ill patients may need hospitalization, while nontoxic patients can be treated at home with bed rest, analgesics, stool softeners, and hydration.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Men with acute prostatitis complicated by urinary retention are best managed with a suprapubic catheter or intermittent catheterization.
[src:azoospermia/acute-prostatitis] Lack of clinical response to antibiotics should raise the suspicion of an abscess and prompt an imaging study such as a transrectal ultrasound (TRUS).
[src:azoospermia/agenesis] In medicine, **agenesis** (/eɪˈdʒɛnəsəs/) refers to the failure of an organ to develop during embryonic growth and development due to the absence of primordial tissue.
[src:azoospermia/agenesis] Because the middle and inner ears are necessary for hearing, people with complete agenesis of the ears are totally deaf.
[src:azoospermia/agenesis] Minor agenesis that affects only the visible parts of the outer ear, which may be called microtia, typically produces cosmetic concerns and perhaps hearing impairment if the opening to the ear canal is blocked, but not deafness.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a variety of adverse effects.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Short-term adverse effects include generalized impairment of neurocognitive function, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, and symptoms of hangover.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is addictive and can result in alcohol use disorder, dependence, and withdrawal upon cessation.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The adverse effects of alcohol on health are most significant when it is used in excessive quantities or with heavy frequency.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] However, in 2023, the World Health Organization published a statement in The Lancet Public Health that concluded, "no safe amount of alcohol consumption for cancers and health can be established".
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] In high amounts, alcohol may cause loss of consciousness or, in severe cases, death.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Many governmental agencies and organizations issue alcohol consumption recommendations.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has been produced and consumed by humans for its psychoactive effects since at least 13,000 years ago, when the earliest known beer was brewed by the Natufian culture in the Middle East.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is the second most consumed psychoactive drug globally, behind caffeine, with global sales of alcoholic beverages exceeding US$1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Drinking alcohol is generally socially acceptable and is legal in most countries, unlike with many other recreational substances.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] However, there are often restrictions on alcohol sale and use, for instance a minimum age for drinking and laws against public drinking and drinking and driving.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has considerable societal and cultural significance and has important social roles in much of the world.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Drinking establishments, such as bars and nightclubs, revolve primarily around the sale and consumption of alcoholic beverages, and parties, festivals, and social gatherings commonly involve alcohol consumption.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is related to various societal problems, including drunk driving, accidental injuries, sexual assaults, domestic abuse, and violent crime.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol remains illegal for sale and consumption in a number of countries, mainly in the Middle East.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] While some religions, including Islam, prohibit alcohol consumption, other religions, such as Christianity and Shinto, utilize alcohol in sacrament and libation.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is commonly consumed as the recreational active substance of alcoholic beverages such as beer, wine, and spirits.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Consumption in social settings may enhance sociability.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] While research on the societal benefits of alcohol is rare, in a study from the UK, regular but moderate drinking was correlated with happiness, feeling that life was worthwhile, and satisfaction with life.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Community pubs had less variation in visible group sizes and longer, more focused conversations than those in city centre bars.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Drinking regularly at a community pub led to higher trust in others and better networking with the local community, compared to non-drinkers and city centre bar drinkers.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] However, according to a causal path analysis, alcohol consumption was not the cause, but rather satisfaction with life resulted in greater happiness and an inclination to visit pubs and develop a regular drinking venue.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The US Department of Agriculture (USDA) uses a figure of 6.93 kilocalories (29.0 kJ) per gram of alcohol (5.47 kcal or 22.9 kJ per mL) for calculating food energy.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] For distilled spirits, a standard serving in the United States is 44 mL (1.5 US fl oz), which at 40% ethanol (80 proof), would be 14 grams and 98 calories.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic drinks are considered empty calorie foods because other than food energy they contribute no essential nutrients.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] However, alcohol is a significant source of food energy for individuals with alcoholism and those who engage in binge drinking.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] For example, individuals with drunkorexia engage in the combination of self-imposed malnutrition and binge drinking.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] In alcoholics who get most of their daily calories from alcohol, a deficiency of thiamine (vitamin B1) can produce Korsakoff syndrome, which is associated with serious brain damage.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] When fomepizole is not available, ethanol can be used to treat or prevent methanol or ethylene glycol poisoning.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The rate-limiting steps for the elimination of ethanol are in common with these substances, so it competes with other alcohols for the alcohol dehydrogenase enzyme.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Methanol itself is not highly toxic, but its metabolites formaldehyde and formic acid are; therefore, to reduce the rate of production and concentration of these harmful metabolites, ethanol can be ingested or injected.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] This avoids the production of toxic aldehyde and carboxylic acid derivatives, and reduces the more serious toxic effects of the glycols when crystallized in the kidneys.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethylene glycol poisoning can be treated in the same way.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a long association of military use, and has been called "liquid courage" for its role in preparing troops for battle, anesthetize injured soldiers, and celebrate military victories.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] It has also served as a coping mechanism for combat stress reactions and a means of decompression from combat to everyday life.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol can have analgesic (pain-relieving) effects, which is why some people with chronic pain turn to alcohol to self-medicate and try to alleviate their physical discomfort.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] People with social anxiety disorder commonly self-medicate with alcohol to overcome their highly set inhibitions.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] However, self-medicating excessively for prolonged periods of time with alcohol often makes the symptoms of anxiety or depression worse.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] This is believed to occur as a result of the changes in brain chemistry from long-term use.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] A 2023 systematic review highlights the non-addictive use of alcohol for managing developmental issues, personality traits, and psychiatric symptoms, emphasizing the need for informed, harm-controlled approaches to alcohol consumption within a personalized health policy framework.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is classified as a teratogen—a substance known to cause birth defects; according to the U.S.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), alcohol consumption by women who are not using birth control increases the risk of fetal alcohol spectrum disorders (FASDs).
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] This group of conditions encompasses fetal alcohol syndrome, partial fetal alcohol syndrome, alcohol-related neurodevelopmental disorder, static encephalopathy, and alcohol-related birth defects.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The CDC currently recommends complete abstinence from alcoholic beverages for women of child-bearing age who are pregnant or trying to become pregnant.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] In patients who have a peptic ulcer disease (PUD), the mucosal layer is broken down by ethanol.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] PUD is commonly associated with the bacteria *Helicobacter pylori*, which secretes a toxin that weakens the mucosal wall, allowing acid and protein enzymes to penetrate the weakened barrier.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Because alcohol stimulates the stomach to secrete acid, a person with PUD should avoid drinking alcohol on an empty stomach.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Drinking alcohol causes more acid release, which further damages the already-weakened stomach wall.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Complications of this disease could include a burning pain in the abdomen, bloating, and, in severe cases, the presence of dark black stools indicate internal bleeding.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] A person who drinks alcohol regularly is strongly advised to reduce their intake to prevent PUD aggravation.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol-containing beverages can cause alcohol flush reactions, exacerbations of rhinitis, and, more seriously and commonly, bronchoconstriction in patients with a history of asthma, and in some cases, urticarial skin eruptions, and systemic dermatitis.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol consumption can cause hypoglycemia in diabetics on certain medications, such as insulin or sulfonylurea, by blocking gluconeogenesis.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol increases insulin response to glucose promoting fat storage and hindering carbohydrate and fat oxidation.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] This excess processing in the liver acetyl CoA can lead to fatty liver disease and eventually alcoholic liver disease.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] This progression can lead to further complications, alcohol-related liver disease may cause exocrine pancreatic insufficiency, the inability to properly digest food due to a lack or reduction of digestive enzymes made by the pancreas.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a variety of short-term and long-term adverse effects.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has both short-term, and long-term effects on the memory, and sleep.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] It also has reinforcement-related adverse effects, including alcoholism, dependence, and withdrawal.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol use is directly related to considerable morbidity and mortality, for instance due to intoxication and alcohol-related health problems.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The World Health Organization advises that there is no safe level of alcohol consumption.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Many of the toxic and unpleasant actions of alcohol in the body are mediated by its carcinogenic byproduct acetaldehyde.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The amount of ethanol in the body is typically quantified by blood alcohol content (BAC); weight of ethanol per unit volume of blood.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Small doses of ethanol, in general, are stimulant-like and produce euphoria and relaxation; people experiencing these symptoms tend to become talkative and less inhibited, and may exhibit poor judgement.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] At higher dosages (BAC > 1 gram/liter), ethanol acts as a central nervous system (CNS) depressant, producing at progressively higher dosages, impaired sensory and motor function, slowed cognition, stupefaction, unconsciousness, and possible death.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] A hangover is the experience of various unpleasant physiological and psychological effects usually following the consumption of alcohol, such as wine, beer, and liquor.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Hangovers can last for several hours or for more than 24 hours.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The long-term effects of alcohol have been extensively researched.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The health effects of long-term alcohol consumption vary depending on the amount consumed.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Even light drinking poses health risks, but atypically small amounts of alcohol may have health benefits.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholism causes severe health consequences which outweigh any potential benefits.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Long-term alcohol consumption is capable of damaging nearly every organ and system in the body.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] In addition, damage to the central nervous system and peripheral nervous system (e.g., painful peripheral neuropathy) can occur from chronic heavy alcohol consumption.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] There is also an increased risk for accidental injuries, for example, those sustained in traffic accidents and falls.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Excessive alcohol consumption can have a negative impact on aging.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Conversely, light intake of alcohol may have some beneficial effects.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The association of alcohol intake with reduced cardiovascular risk has been noted since 1904 and remains even after adjusting for known confounders.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Light alcohol intake is also associated with reduced risk of type 2 diabetes, gastritis, and cholelithiasis.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] However, these are only observational studies and high-quality evidence for the beneficial effects of alcohol is nonexistent.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol causes a plethora of detrimental effects in society.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Addiction experts in psychiatry, chemistry, pharmacology, forensic science, epidemiology, and the police and legal services engaged in delphic analysis regarding 20 popular recreational substances.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol was ranked 6th in dependence, 11th in physical harm, and 2nd in social harm.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol use is stereotypically associated with crime, more so than other drugs like marijuana.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Many emergency room visits involve alcohol use.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] As many as 15% of employees show problematic alcohol-related behaviors in the workplace, such as drinking before going to work or even drinking on the job.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Drunk dialing refers to an intoxicated person making phone calls that they would not likely make if sober.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol availability and consumption rates and alcohol rates are positively associated with nuisance, loitering, panhandling, and disorderly conduct in open spaces.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Binge drinking, or heavy episodic drinking, is drinking alcoholic beverages with an intention of becoming intoxicated by heavy consumption of alcohol over a short period of time.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Binge drinking is associated with risks such as suicide, sexual assault, cardiovascular issues, and brain damage, more acutely than alcohol use in general.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholism or its medical diagnosis *alcohol use disorder* refers to alcohol addiction, alcohol dependence, dipsomania, and/or alcohol abuse.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] It is a major problem and many health problems as well as death can result from excessive alcohol use.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol dependence is linked to a lifespan that is reduced by about 12 years relative to the average person.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] In 2004, it was estimated that 4% of deaths worldwide were attributable to alcohol use.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Deaths from alcohol are split about evenly between acute causes (e.g., overdose, accidents) and chronic conditions.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The leading chronic alcohol-related condition associated with death is alcoholic liver disease.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol dependence is also associated with cognitive impairment and organic brain damage.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Some researchers have found that even one alcoholic drink a day increases an individual's risk of health problems by 0.4%.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Two or more consecutive alcohol-free days a week have been recommended to improve health and break dependence.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Discontinuation of alcohol after extended heavy use and associated tolerance development (resulting in dependence) can result in alcohol withdrawal.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is one of the most dangerous drugs to withdraw from.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol withdrawal can cause confusion, paranoia, anxiety, insomnia, agitation, tremors, fever, nausea, vomiting, autonomic dysfunction, seizures, and hallucinations.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Delirium tremens is a condition that develops in some cases of severe withdrawal, with onset typically 48–72 hours after discontinuation.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] It is considered a medical emergency and should be treated in an inpatient or intensive care unit.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Symptoms of ethanol overdose may include nausea, vomiting, CNS depression, coma, acute respiratory failure, or death.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Levels of even less than 0.1% can cause intoxication, with unconsciousness often occurring at 0.3–0.4%.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Death from ethanol consumption is possible when blood alcohol levels reach 0.4%.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] A blood level of 0.5% or more is commonly fatal.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The oral median lethal dose (LD50) of ethanol in rats is 5,628 mg/kg.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Directly translated to human beings, this would mean that if a person who weighs 70 kg (150 lb) drank a 500 mL (17 US fl oz) glass of pure ethanol, they would have an estimated 50% risk of dying.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The highest blood alcohol level ever recorded, in which the subject survived, is 1.41%.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol-induced dose dumping (AIDD) is an unintended rapid release of large amounts of a given drug, when administered through a modified-release dosage while co-ingesting ethanol.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] This is considered a pharmaceutical disadvantage due to the high risk of causing drug-induced toxicity by increasing the absorption and serum concentration above the therapeutic window of the drug.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The best way to prevent this interaction is by avoiding the co-ingestion of both substances or using specific controlled-release formulations that are resistant to AIDD.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Particular drugs of concern are antipsychotics and certain antidepressants.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol can intensify the sedation caused by hypnotics and sedatives such as barbiturates, benzodiazepines, sedative antihistamines, opioids, nonbenzodiazepines/Z-drugs (such as zolpidem and zopiclone).
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Disulfiram inhibits the enzyme acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, which in turn results in buildup of acetaldehyde, a toxic metabolite of ethanol with unpleasant effects.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The medication or drug is commonly used to treat alcohol use disorder, and results in immediate hangover-like symptoms upon consumption of alcohol, this effect is widely known as disulfiram effect.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Metronidazole is an antibacterial agent that kills bacteria by damaging cellular DNA and hence cellular function.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Metronidazole is usually given to people who have diarrhea caused by *Clostridioides difficile* bacteria.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Patients who are taking metronidazole are sometimes advised to avoid alcohol, even after 1 hour following the last dose.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Although older data suggested a possible disulfiram-like effect of metronidazole, newer data has challenged this and suggests it does not actually have this effect.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) and alcohol both increase gastrointestinal events such as gastrointestinal bleeding and peptic ulcers.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Taking the two together further increases the risk additively.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The risk of stomach bleeding is still increased when aspirin is taken with alcohol or warfarin.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol enhances the bioavailability of methylphenidate (elevated plasma dexmethylphenidate).
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethylphenidate formation appears to be more common when large quantities of methylphenidate and alcohol are consumed at the same time, such as in non-medical use or overdose scenarios.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] However, only a small percent of the consumed methylphenidate is converted to ethylphenidate.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] While nicotinis mimic the name of classic cocktails like the appletini (their name deriving from "martini"), combining nicotine with alcohol may cause adverse effects.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Tobacco and nicotine actually heighten cravings for alcohol, making this a risky mix.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Controlled animal and human studies showed that caffeine (energy drinks) in combination with alcohol increased the craving for more alcohol more strongly than alcohol alone.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] These findings correspond to epidemiological data that people who consume energy drinks generally showed an increased tendency to take alcohol and other substances.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol interacts with cocaine *in vivo* to produce cocaethylene, another psychoactive substance which may be substantially more cardiotoxic than either cocaine or alcohol by themselves.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] In combination with cannabis, ethanol increases plasma tetrahydrocannabinol levels, which suggests that ethanol may increase the absorption of tetrahydrocannabinol.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Excessive use of alcohol is known to affect the metabolism of warfarin and can elevate the INR, and thus increase the risk of bleeding.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) product insert on warfarin states that alcohol should be avoided.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The Cleveland Clinic suggests that when taking warfarin one should not drink more than "one beer, 6 oz of wine, or one shot of alcohol per day".
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Use of isoniazid should be carefully monitored in daily alcohol drinkers since they may be more likely to develop isoniazid-associated hepatitis.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol works in the brain primarily by increasing the effects of GABA (γ-aminobutyric acid), the major inhibitory neurotransmitter in the brain; by facilitating GABA's actions in the GABAA receptor, alcohol suppresses the activity of the central nervous system.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol also directly affects a number of other neurotransmitter systems including those of glutamate, glycine, acetylcholine, and serotonin.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The pleasurable effects of alcohol ingestion are the result of increased levels of dopamine and endogenous opioids in the reward pathways of the brain.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] After oral ingestion, ethanol is absorbed via the stomach and intestines into the bloodstream.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is highly water-soluble and diffuses passively throughout the entire body, including the brain.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Soon after ingestion, it begins to be metabolized, 90% or more by the liver.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] One standard drink is sufficient to almost completely saturate the liver's capacity to metabolize alcohol.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The main metabolite is acetaldehyde, a toxic carcinogen.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Acetaldehyde is then further metabolized into ionic acetate by the enzyme aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH).
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Acetate is not carcinogenic and has low toxicity, but has been implicated in causing hangovers.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Acetate is further broken down into carbon dioxide and water and eventually eliminated from the body through urine and breath.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] 5 to 10% of ethanol is excreted unchanged in the breath, urine, and sweat.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is also known chemically as alcohol, ethyl alcohol, or drinking alcohol.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] It is a simple alcohol with a molecular formula of C2H6O and a molecular weight of 46.0684 g/mol.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The molecular formula of ethanol may also be written as CH3−CH2−OH or as C2H5−OH.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The latter can also be thought of as an ethyl group linked to a hydroxyl (alcohol) group and can be abbreviated as EtOH.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is a volatile, flammable, colorless liquid with a slight characteristic odor.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Aside from its use as a psychoactive and recreational substance, ethanol is also commonly used as an antiseptic and disinfectant, a chemical and medicinal solvent, and a fuel.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is only one of several types of chemical alcohols, and has a variety of analogues.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Most other alcohols are considered poisonous.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] In general, higher alcohols are less toxic.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic beverages are sometimes laced with toxic alcohols.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The toxicity of isopropyl alcohol is about twice that of ethanol; a mild, brief exposure to isopropyl alcohol is unlikely to cause any serious harm, although ingesting significant quantities can lead to vomiting, abdominal pain, and internal bleeding.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ingestion of as little as 3.16 grams of methanol can cause irreversible optic nerve damage, and the oral LD50 for humans is estimated to be 56.2 grams.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Many methanol poisoning incidents have occurred through history. n-Butanol is reported to produce similar effects to those of ethanol and relatively low toxicity (one-sixth of that of ethanol in one rat study).
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] However, its vapors can produce eye irritation, and inhalation can cause pulmonary edema.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Acetone (propanone) is a ketone rather than an alcohol, and is reported to produce similar toxic effects; it can be extremely damaging to the cornea.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Although ethanol is the most prevalent alcohol in alcoholic beverages, alcoholic beverages contain several types of psychoactive alcohols, that are categorized as primary, secondary, or tertiary.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Primary and secondary alcohols, are oxidized to aldehydes, and ketones, respectively, while tertiary alcohols are generally resistant to oxidation.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The Lucas test differentiates between primary, secondary, and tertiary alcohols.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The tertiary alcohol *tert*-amyl alcohol (TAA), also known as 2-methylbutan-2-ol (2M2B), has a history of use as a hypnotic and anesthetic, as do other tertiary alcohols such as methylpentynol, ethchlorvynol, and chloralodol.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Unlike primary alcohols like ethanol, these tertiary alcohols cannot be oxidized into aldehyde or carboxylic acid metabolites, which are often toxic, and for this reason, these compounds are safer in comparison.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Other relatives of ethanol with similar effects include chloral hydrate, paraldehyde, and many volatile and inhalational anesthetics (e.g., chloroform, diethyl ether, and isoflurane).
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is produced naturally as a byproduct of the metabolic processes of yeast and hence is present in any yeast habitat, including even endogenously in humans, but it does not cause raised blood alcohol content as seen in the rare medical condition auto-brewery syndrome (ABS).
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] It is manufactured through hydration of ethylene or by brewing via fermentation of sugars with yeast (most commonly *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*).
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The sugars are commonly obtained from sources like steeped cereal grains (e.g., barley), grape juice, and sugarcane products (e.g., molasses, sugarcane juice).
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol–water mixture which can be further purified via distillation.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is one of the oldest recreational drugs.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The word "Alcohol" originates from the Arabic word *al-kuhul,* which refers to a fine metallic powder that was used to paint the eyelids darker.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic beverages have been produced since the Neolithic period, as early as 7000 BC in China.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol was brewed as early as 7,000 to 6,650 BCE in northern China.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The earliest evidence of winemaking was dated at 6,000 to 5,800 BCE in Georgia in the South Caucasus.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Beer was likely brewed from barley as early as 13,000 years ago in the Middle East.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Pliny the Elder wrote about the *golden age* of winemaking in Rome, the 2nd century BCE (200–100 BCE), when vineyards were planted.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The Gin Craze was a period in the first half of the 18th century when the consumption of gin increased rapidly in Great Britain, especially in London.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] By 1743, The average English person was drinking 2.2 gallons (10 litres) of gin per year.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The Sale of Spirits Act 1750 (commonly known as the Gin Act 1751) was an Act of the Parliament of Great Britain (24 Geo.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] 40) which was enacted to reduce the consumption of gin and other distilled spirits, a popular pastime that was regarded as one of the primary causes of crime in London.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The rum ration (also called the tot) was a daily amount of rum given to sailors on Royal Navy ships.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] It started 1866 and was abolished in 1970 after concerns that the intake of strong alcohol would lead to unsteady hands when working machinery.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The Andrew Johnson alcoholism debate is the dispute, originally conducted among the general public, and now typically a question for historians, about whether or not Andrew Johnson, the 17th president of the United States (1865–1869), drank to excess.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The prohibition in the United States era was the period from 1920 to 1933 when the United States prohibited the production, importation, transportation, and sale of alcoholic beverages.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The nationwide ban on alcoholic beverages, was repealed by the passage of the Twenty-first Amendment to the United States Constitution on December 5, 1933.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The Bratt System was a system that was used in Sweden (1919–1955) and similarly in Finland (1944–1970) to control alcohol consumption, by rationing of liquor.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Every citizen allowed to consume alcohol was given a booklet called a motbok (viinakortti in Finland), in which a stamp was added each time a purchase was made at Systembolaget (in Sweden) and Alko (in Finland).
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] A similar system also existed in Estonia between July 1, 1920, to December 31, 1925.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The stamps were based on the amount of alcohol bought.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] When a certain amount of alcohol had been bought, the owner of the booklet had to wait until next month to buy more.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The Medicinal Liquor Prescriptions Act of 1933 was a law passed by Congress in response to the abuse of medicinal liquor prescriptions during Prohibition.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Gilbert Paul Jordan (aka The Boozing Barber) was a Canadian serial killer who is believed to have committed the so-called "alcohol murders" between 1965–c.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The consumption of alcohol is deeply embedded in social practices and rituals, often celebrated as a cornerstone of community gatherings and personal milestones.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Drinking culture is the set of traditions and social behaviours that surround the consumption of alcoholic beverages as a recreational drug and social lubricant.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol consumption is fully legal and available in most countries of the world.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Home made alcoholic beverages with low alcohol content like wine, and beer is also legal in most countries, but distilling moonshine outside of a registered distillery remains illegal in most of them.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Some majority-Muslim countries, such as Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Pakistan, Iran, and Libya prohibit the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages because they are forbidden by Islam.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Also, laws banning alcohol consumption are found in some Indian states as well as some Native American reservations in the U.S.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] In addition, there are regulations on alcohol sales and use in many countries throughout the world.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] For instance, the majority of countries have a minimum legal drinking age to purchase or consume alcoholic beverages, although there are often exceptions such as underage consumption of small amounts of alcohol with parental supervision.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Also, some countries have bans on public intoxication.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Drinking while driving or intoxicated driving is frequently outlawed, and it may be illegal to have an open container of alcohol or liquor bottle in an automobile, bus, or aircraft.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The legality of sex under alcohol influence varies by country and the threshold of "too drunk" for sexual consent can be ambiguous.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Religion and alcohol have a complex history.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The world's religions have had different relationships with alcohol, reflecting diverse cultural, social, and religious practices across different traditions.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] While some religions strictly prohibit alcohol consumption, viewing it as sinful or harmful to spiritual and physical well-being, others incorporate it into their rituals and ceremonies.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Throughout history, alcohol has held significant roles in religious observances, from the use of sacramental wine in Christian sacraments to the offering and moderate drinking of omiki (sacramental sake) in Shinto purification rituals.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] A study in 2015 found that alcohol and tobacco use combined resulted in a significant health burden, costing over a quarter of a billion disability-adjusted life years.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Illicit drug use caused tens of millions more disability-adjusted life years.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] According to *The Lancet*, 'four industries (tobacco, unhealthy food, fossil fuel, and alcohol) are responsible for at least a third of global deaths per year'.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] In 2024, the World Health Organization published a report including these figures.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Many Native Americans in the United States have been harmed by, or become addicted to, drinking alcohol.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] Qualitative analysis reveals that the alcohol industry likely misinforms the public about the dangers of alcohol, similar to the tobacco industry.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The alcohol industry influences alcohol policy and health messages, including those for schoolchildren.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The alcohol consumption recommendations (or *safe limits*) varies from no intake, to daily, weekly, or daily/weekly guidelines provided by health agencies of governments.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] A standard drink is a measure of alcohol consumption representing a fixed amount of pure ethanol, used in relation to recommendations about alcohol consumption and its relative risks to health.
[src:azoospermia/alcohol-drug] The size of a standard drink varies from 8g to 20g across countries, but 10g alcohol (12.7 millilitres) is used in the World Health Organization (WHO) Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test (AUDIT)'s questionnaire form example, and has been adopted by more countries than any other amount.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Historically, alpha-blockers were used as a tool for pharmacologic research to develop a greater understanding of the autonomic nervous system.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Using alpha blockers, scientists began characterizing arterial blood pressure and central vasomotor control in the autonomic nervous system.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Today, they can be used as clinical treatments for a limited number of diseases.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Alpha blockers can treat a small range of diseases such as hypertension, Raynaud's disease, benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) and erectile dysfunction.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Generally speaking, these treatments function by binding an α-blocker to α receptors in the arteries and smooth muscle.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Ultimately, depending on the type of alpha receptor, this relaxes the smooth muscle or blood vessels, which increases fluid flow in these entities.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] When the term "alpha blocker" is used without further qualification, it can refer to an α1 blocker, an α2 blocker, a nonselective blocker (both α1 and α2 activity), or an α blocker with some β activity.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] However, the most common type of alpha blocker is α1.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Finally, the agents carvedilol and labetalol are both α and β-blockers.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Below are some of the most common drugs used in the clinic.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] While there are limited clinical α-blocker uses, in which most α-blockers are used for hypertension or benign prostatic hyperplasia, α-blockers can be used to treat a few other diseases, such as Raynaud's disease, congestive heart failure (CHF), pheochromocytoma, and erectile dysfunction.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Furthermore, α-blockers can occasionally be used to treat anxiety and panic disorders, such as posttraumatic stress disorder (PTSD) induced nightmares.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Studies have also had great medical interest in testing alpha blockers, specifically α2 blockers, to treat type II diabetes and psychiatric depression.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Hypertension is due to an increase in vascular resistance and vasoconstriction.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Using α1 selective antagonists, such as prazosin, has been efficacious in treating mild to moderate hypertension.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] This is because they can decrease vascular resistance and decrease pressure.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] However, while these drugs are generally well tolerated, they have the potential to produce side effects such as orthostatic hypotension and dizziness.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] However, unlike other treatments for hypertension such as ACE inhibitors, ARBs, calcium channel blockers, thiazide diuretics or beta blockers, alpha blockers have not demonstrated the same mortality and morbidity benefits, and are therefore not generally used as first or even second line agents.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Another treatment for hypertension is using drugs that have both α1 blocking activity, as well as nonselective β activity, such as Labetalol or carvedilol.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] In low doses, labetalol and carvedilol can decrease the peripheral resistance and block the effects of isoprenaline to reduce hypertensive symptoms.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Pheochromocytoma is a disease in which a catecholamine secreting tumor develops.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Specifically, norepinephrine and epinephrine are secreted by these tumors, either continuously or intermittently.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] The excess release of these catecholamines increases central nervous system stimulation, thus causing blood vessels to increase in vascular resistance, and ultimately giving rise to hypertension.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] In addition, patients with these rare tumors are often subject to headaches, heart palpitations, and increased sweating.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Phenoxybenzamine, a nonselective α1 and α2 blocker, has been used to treat pheochromocytoma.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] This drug blocks the activity of epinephrine and norepinephrine by antagonizing the alpha receptors, thus decreasing vascular resistance, increasing vasodilation, and decreasing blood pressure overall.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Blockers that have both the ability to block both α and β receptors, such as carvedilol, bucindolol, and labetalol, have the ability to mitigate the symptoms in congestive heart failure.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] By binding to both the α and β receptors, these drugs can decrease the cardiac output and stimulate the dilation of blood vessels to promote a reduction in blood pressure.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Yohimbine, an α2 blocker derived from the bark of the *Pausinystalia johimbe* tree, has been tested to increase libido and treat erectile dysfunction.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] The proposed mechanism for yohimbine is blockade of the adrenergic receptors that are associated with neurotransmitters inhibition, including dopamine and nitric oxide, and thus aiding with penile erection and libido.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] By doing so, they can alter the blood flow in the penis to aid in achieving an erection.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] However, some side effects can occur, such as palpitation, tremor, elevated blood pressure, and anxiety.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Yohimbe bark contains both α1 and α2 adrenergic receptors blocking alkaloids.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Phentolamine, a non-selective alpha blocker, has also been tested to treat erectile dysfunction.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] By reducing vasoconstriction in the penis, there appears to be increased blood flow that aids in penile erection.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Side effects associated with phentolamine include headache, flushing, and nasal congestion.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Phenoxybenzamine, a non-competitive α1 and α2 blocker was used by Dr.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Giles Brindley in the first intracavernosal pharmacotherapy for erectile dysfunction.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] In benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), men experience urinary obstruction and are unable to urinate, thus leading to urinary retention. α1 specific blockers have been used to relax the smooth muscle in the bladder and enlarged prostate.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Prazosin, doxazosin, and terazosin have been particularly useful for patients with BPH, especially in patients with hypertension.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] In such patients, these drugs can treat both conditions at the same time.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] In patients without hypertension, tamsulosin can be used, as it has the ability to relax the bladder and prostate smooth muscle without causing major changes in blood pressure.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Both α1 blockers and α2 blockers have been examined to treat Raynaud's disease.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Although α1 blockers, such as prazosin, have appeared to give slight improvement for the sclerotic symptoms of Raynaud's disease, there are many side effects that occur while taking this drug.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Conversely, α2 blockers, such as yohimbine, appear to provide significant improvement of the sclerotic symptoms in Raynaud's Disease without excessive side effects.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Patients with posttraumatic stress disorder (PTSD) have often continued to be symptomatic despite being treated with PTSD-specific drugs.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] In addition, PTSD patients often have debilitating nightmares that continue, despite their treatments.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] High doses of the α1 blocker, prazosin, have been efficacious in treating patients with PTSD induced nightmares due to its ability to block the effects of norepinephrine.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Adverse effects of prazosin to treat PTSD nightmares include dizziness, first dose effect (a sudden loss of consciousness), weakness, nausea, and fatigue.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Although alpha blockers have the ability to reduce some disease pathology, there are some side effects that come with these alpha blockers.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] However, because there are several structural compositions that make each alpha blocker different, the side effects are different for each drug.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Side effects that arise when taking alpha blockers can include the first dose effect, cardiovascular side effects, genitourinary side effects, as well as other side effects.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] One of the most common side effects with alpha blockers is the first dose effect.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] This is a phenomenon in which patients with hypertension take an alpha blocker for the first time, and suddenly experience an intense decrease in blood pressure.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Ultimately, this gives rise to orthostatic hypotension, dizziness, and a sudden loss of consciousness due to the drastic drop in blood pressure.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Alpha blockers that possess these side effects include prazosin, doxazosin, and terazosin.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] There are some alpha blockers that can give rise to changes in the cardiovascular system, such as the induction of reflex tachycardia, orthostatic hypotension, or heart palpitations via alterations of the QT interval.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Alpha blockers that may have these side effects include yohimbine, phenoxybenzamine, and phentolamine.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] When alpha blockers are used to treat BPH, it causes vasodilation of blood vessels on the bladder and the prostate, thus increasing urination in general.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] However, these alpha blockers can produce the exact opposite side effect, in which edema, or abnormal fluid retention, occurs.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] In addition, due to the relaxation of the prostate smooth muscle, another side effect that arises in men being treated for BPH is impotence, as well as the inability to ejaculate.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] However, if any ejaculation activity does occur, oftentimes, it results in a phenomenon called retrograde ejaculation, in which semen flows into the urinary bladder instead of exiting through the urethra.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Drugs that may produce such side effects include prazosin, terazosin, tamsulosin, and doxazosin.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Finally, there are other general side effects that can be caused by most alpha blockers (however, more frequently in alpha-1 blockers).
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Such side effects include dizziness, drowsiness, weakness, fatigue, psychiatric depression, and dry mouth.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Priapism, an unwanted, painful long term erection not brought on by sexual arousal and lasting several hours has been associated with alpha blocker use.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] While this is extremely rare, particularly with tamsulosin, it can cause permanent impotence if not treated in a hospital setting.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Male patients should be made aware of this as it can result from a single dose or develop over time.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] There is only one compelling indication for alpha blockers, which is for benign prostatic hyperplasia.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Patients who need alpha blockers for BPH, but have a history of hypotension or postural heart failure, should use these drugs with caution, as it may result in an even greater decrease in blood pressure or make heart failure even worse.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] The most compelling contraindication is urinary incontinence and overall fluid retention.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] To combat such fluid retention, patients can take a diuretic in combination with the alpha-blocker.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] As with any drug, there are drug interactions that can occur with alpha blockers.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] For instance, alpha blockers that are used for the reduction of blood pressure, such as phenoxybenzamine or phentolamine can have synergy with other drugs that affect smooth muscle, blood vessels, or drugs used for erectile dysfunction (i.e. sildenafil, tamsulosin, etc.).
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] This stimulates exaggerated hypotension.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Alternative alpha blockers, such as prazosin, tamsulosin, doxazosin, or terazosin can have adverse interactions with beta blockers, erectile dysfunction drugs, anxiolytics, and antihistamines.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Again, these interactions can cause dangerous hypotension.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Furthermore, in rare cases, drug interactions can cause irregular, rapid heartbeats or an increase blood pressure.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Yohimbine can interact with stimulants, hypertension drugs, naloxone, and clonidine.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Interactions with such drugs can cause either an unintended increase in blood pressure or potentiate an increase in blood pressure.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Finally, in drugs with both alpha and beta blocking properties, such as carvedilol and labetalol, interactions with other alpha or beta blockers can exaggerate a decrease in blood pressure.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Conversely, there are also drug interactions with carvedilol or labetalol in which blood pressure is increased unintentionally (such as with cough and cold medications).
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Finally, there may also be some alpha/beta blocker drug interactions that can worsen previous heart failure.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Alpha blockers work by blocking the effect of nerves in the sympathetic nervous system.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] This is done by binding to the alpha receptors in smooth muscle or blood vessels. α-blockers can bind both reversibly and irreversibly.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] There are several α receptors throughout the body where these drugs can bind.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Specifically, α1 receptors can be found in most vascular smooth muscle, the pupillary dilator muscle, the heart, the prostate, and pilomotor smooth muscle.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] On the other hand, α2 receptors can be found in platelets, cholinergic nerve terminals, some vascular smooth muscle, postsynaptic CNS neurons, and fat cells.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] The structure of α receptors is a classic G protein–coupled receptors (GPCRs) consisting of 7 transmembrane domains, which form three intracellular loops and three extracellular loops.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] These receptors couple to heterotrimeric G proteins composed of α, β, and γ subunits.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Although both of the α receptors are GPCRs, there are large differences in their mechanism of action.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Specifically, α1 receptors are characterized as Gq GPCRs, signaling through Phospholipase C to increase IP3 and DAG, thus increasing the release of calcium.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Meanwhile, α2 receptors are labeled as Gi GPCRs, which signal through adenylyl cyclase to decrease cAMP.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] Because the α1 and α2 receptors have different mechanisms of action, their antagonists also have different effects. α1 blockers can inhibit the release of IP3 and DAG to decrease calcium release, thus, decreasing overall signaling.
[src:azoospermia/alpha-blocker] On the other hand, α2 blockers prevent the reduction of cAMP, thus leading to an increase in overall signaling.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] The **American Society for Reproductive Medicine** (**ASRM**) is a nonprofit, multidisciplinary organization for advancement of the science and practice of reproductive medicine.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] The society has its headquarters in Washington, D.C., and its administrative office in Birmingham, Alabama.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] An associated special interest group, the **Society for Assisted Reproductive Technology (SART)**, maintains a national registry for tracking IVF attempts and outcomes.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] Founded in 1944 by a small group of fertility experts who met in Chicago, the initial name was the **American Society for the Study of Sterility**, changed in 1965 to **American Fertility Society (AFS)**.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] The current name, American Society for Reproductive Medicine, was adopted in 1994.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] In 2018, ASRM created its own research institute.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] In 2019, it moved its headquarters to Washington, D.C., from Birmingham, Alabama.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] Though primarily an American organization, it had members from over 100 countries as of 2020.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] The society hosts an annual scientific congress, as well as courses, seminars, workshops and publications.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] Special interest groups are focused on a range of reproductive medicine topics.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] ASRM has an Ethics Committee that provides guidance on ethical issues.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] The ASRM Practice Committee issues clinical guidelines and reports.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] The **Society for Assisted Reproductive Technology** (SART) is described as a sister organization or special interest group associated with the American Society for Reproductive Medicine.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] SART was founded in 1985 by Alan DeCherney and Richard Marrs, with the goal of establishing a national registry to track IVF attempts and outcomes.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] As of 2014, 375 member clinics were registered with SART in the United States, accounting for 91% of all reported ART cycles.
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] Data are tabulated at clinics, gathered, and reported nationally to the SART Clinical Outcomes Reporting System (CORS) and National ART Surveillance System (NASS).
[src:azoospermia/american-society-for-reproductive-medicine] In May 2014, the ASRM became an associated non-state actor (NSA) with the World Health Organization (WHO).
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] In a non-pathological context, azoospermia is also the intended result of a vasectomy.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Azoospermia can be classified into three major types.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Many conditions listed may also cause various degrees of oligospermia rather than azoospermia.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Pretesticular and testicular azoospermia are known as non-obstructive azoospermia, whereas post-testicular azoospermia is considered obstructive.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Inadequate stimulation of normal testicles and the genital tract characterizes pretesticular azoospermia.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Typically, follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) levels are low (hypogonadotropic), commensurate with inadequate stimulation of the testes to produce sperm.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Examples include hypopituitarism (for various causes), hyperprolactinemia, and exogenous FSH suppression by testosterone.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Chemotherapy may suppress spermatogenesis.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Pretesticular azoospermia is seen in about 2% of azoospermia.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Pretesticular azoospermia is a kind of non-obstructive azoospermia.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Testicular azoospermia means the testes are abnormal, atrophic, or absent, and sperm production is severely disturbed or absent.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] FSH levels tend to be elevated (hypergonadotropic) as the feedback loop is interrupted (lack of feedback inhibition on FSH).
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] The condition is seen in 49–93% of men with azoospermia.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Testicular failure includes absence of sperm production and low production, and maturation arrest during the process of spermatogenesis.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Causes for testicular failure include congenital issues such as in certain genetic conditions (e.g.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Klinefelter syndrome), some cases of cryptorchidism or Sertoli cell-only syndrome as well as acquired conditions by infection (orchitis), surgery (trauma, cancer), radiation, or other causes.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Mast cells releasing inflammatory mediators appear to directly suppress sperm motility in a potentially reversible manner, and may be a common pathophysiological mechanism for many causes leading to inflammation.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Testicular azoospermia is a kind of non-obstructive azoospermia.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Generally, men with unexplained hypergonadotropic azoospermia need to undergo a chromosomal evaluation.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] In post-testicular azoospermia, sperm are produced but not ejaculated, a condition that affects 7–51% of azoospermic men.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] The main cause is a physical obstruction (obstructive azoospermia) of the post-testicular genital tracts.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] The most common reason is a vasectomy done to induce contraceptive sterility.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Other obstructions can be congenital (for example, agenesis of the vas deferens as seen in certain cases of cystic fibrosis) or acquired, such as ejaculatory duct obstruction for instance by infection.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Ejaculatory disorders include retrograde ejaculation and anejaculation; in these conditions sperm are produced but not expelled.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Idiopathic azoospermia is where there is no known cause of the condition.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] It may be a result of multiple risk factors, such as age and weight.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] For example, a review in 2013 came to the result that oligospermia and azoospermia are significantly associated with being overweight (odds ratio 1.1), obese (odds ratio 1.3) and morbidly obese (odds ratio 2.0), but the cause of this is unknown.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] The review found no significant relation between oligospermia and being underweight.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Pretesticular azoospermia may be caused by congenital hypopituitarism, Kallmann syndrome, Prader-Willi syndrome, and other genetic conditions that lead to GnRH or gonadotropin deficiency.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Testicular azoospermia is seen in Klinefelter syndrome (XXY) and the XX male syndrome.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] In addition, 13% of men with azoospermia have a defective spermatogenesis that is linked to defects of the Y chromosome.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Such defects tend to be de novo micro-deletions and usually affect the long arm of the chromosome.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] A section of the long arm of the Y chromosome has been termed Azoospermia Factor (AZF) at Yq11 and subdivided into AZFa, AZFb, AZFc, and possibly more subsections.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Defects in this area can lead to oligospermia or azoospermia, however, a tight genotype-phenotype correlation has not been achieved.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Spermatogenesis is defective with gene defects for the androgen receptor.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Post-testicular azoospermia can be seen with certain point mutations in the cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator (CFTR) gene, commonly associated with congenital absence of the vas deferens.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Genetic counselling is indicated for men with genetic causes of azoospermia.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Concerning reproduction, it needs to be considered if the genetic defect could be transmitted to the offspring.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] BRD7, a transcription regulatory protein, is normally highly expressed in the testis.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Absent or reduced expression of BRD7 protein was observed in the testes of azoospermia patients exhibiting spermatogenesis arrest.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Homozygous knockout mice [*BRD7*(-/-)] are infertile and have higher levels of apoptosis and DNA damage in their germline cells.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] The human breast cancer susceptibility gene 2 (*BRCA2*) is employed in DNA repair.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] A common single nucleotide polymorphism in *BRCA2* is associated with idiopathic male infertility with azoospermia.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Four genes involved in DNA double-strand break repair and chromosome synapsis (*TEX11*, *TEX15*, *MLH1* and *MLH3*) have key roles in genomic integrity, meiotic recombination and gametogenesis.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Polymorphisms in these genes were tested for associations with male infertility.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Single-nucleotide polymorphisms in two of these genes (*TEX11* and *MLH3*) were found to be associated with male infertility involving azoospermy or oligospermia.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Azoospermia is usually detected in the course of an infertility investigation.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] It is established based on two semen analysis evaluations done on separate occasions (when the seminal specimen, after centrifugation, shows no sperm under the microscope) and requires further work-up.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] The investigation includes a history, a physical examination including a thorough evaluation of the scrotum and testes, laboratory tests, and possibly imaging.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] History includes the general health, sexual health, past fertility, libido, and sexual activity.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] A history of surgical procedures of the genital system needs to be elicited.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] The family history needs to be assessed to look for genetic abnormalities.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Congenital absence of the vas deferens may be detectable on physical examination and can be confirmed by a transrectal ultrasound (TRUS).
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] If confirmed, genetic testing for cystic fibrosis is in order.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Retrograde ejaculation is diagnosed by examining a post-ejaculatory urine for the presence of sperm after making it alkaline and centrifuging it.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Low levels of LH and FSH with low or normal testosterone levels are indicative of pretesticular problems, while high levels of gonadotropins indicate testicular problems.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] However, often this distinction is unclear, and the differentiation between obstructive versus non-obstructive azoospermia may require a testicular biopsy.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Seminal plasma proteins TEX101 and ECM1 were recently proposed for the differential diagnosis of azoospermia forms and subtypes, and for the prediction of TESE outcome.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Mount Sinai Hospital, Canada, started a clinical trial to test this hypothesis in 2016.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Primary hypopituitarism may be linked to a genetic cause.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] So, a genetic evaluation may be done for men with azoospermia as a result.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Azoospermic men with testicular failure are advised to undergo karyotype and Y-micro-deletion testing.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Pre- and post-testicular azoospermia are frequently correctable, while testicular azoospermia is usually permanent.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] In the former, the cause of the azoospermia needs to be considered, and it opens up possibilities to manage this situation directly.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Thus, men with azoospermia due to hyperprolactinemia may resume sperm production after treatment of hyperprolactinemia, or men whose sperm production is suppressed by exogenous androgens are expected to produce sperm after cessation of androgen intake.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] In situations where the testes are normal but unstimulated, gonadotropin therapy can be expected to induce sperm production.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] A major advancement in recent years has been the introduction of IVF with ICSI, which allows successful fertilization even with immature sperm or sperm obtained directly from testicular tissue.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] IVF-ICSI allows for pregnancy in couples where the man has irreversible testicular azoospermia as long as it is possible to recover sperm material from the testes.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Thus, men with non-mosaic Klinefelter's syndrome have fathered children using IVF-ICSI.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Pregnancies have been achieved in situations where azoospermia was associated with cryptorchidism and sperm were obtained by testicular sperm extraction (TESE).
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] In men with post-testicular azoospermia, different approaches are available.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] For obstructive azoospermia, IVF-ICSI or surgery can be used, and individual factors are considered for the choice of treatment.
[src:azoospermia/azoospermia] Medication may be helpful for retrograde ejaculation.
